# Sanad Backend - Project Rules

## Stack & Overview
- **Framework**: NestJS 11
- **Database**: PostgreSQL with Prisma 5
- **Validation**: class-validator, class-transformer
- **Docs**: Swagger at `/api`
- **Auth**: JWT via @nestjs/jwt

## Architecture
Use the **Controller → Service → Repository** pattern:

- **Controller**: HTTP handling, DTOs, Swagger decorators
- **Service**: Business logic, orchestration
- **Repository**: Data access only (extend `BaseRepository`, inject `PrismaService`)

- **Avoid `forwardRef`**: Prefer decoupling modules with `@nestjs/event-emitter`. Have the producer module emit events and the consumer module listen with `@OnEvent()`. Use `emitAsync()` when the emitter needs to wait for the listener (e.g. to get a value back via a mutable event instance). This keeps dependencies one-way and avoids circular module references.

## Event emitter (NestJS sample [30-event-emitter](https://github.com/nestjs/nest/tree/master/sample/30-event-emitter/src))
Follow the structure and placement from the official sample:

- **Event payloads**: Define in `src/<module>/events/` as **classes** in `*.event.ts` files (e.g. `user-registered.event.ts` with `UserRegisteredEvent`). The emitter creates `new MyEvent()`, sets properties, and passes the instance to `emit()` or `emitAsync()`.
- **Event name constants**: Never use magic strings for event names. Define constants in a **constants file in the module that owns the event**: `src/<module>/constants/events.constants.ts`. User events (e.g. `user.registered`) live in the user module’s constants file; OTP events in the otp module’s constants file; and so on. Emitters and listeners (in any module) import and use these constants (e.g. `@OnEvent(USER_REGISTERED_EVENT)`, `emitAsync(USER_REGISTERED_EVENT, event)`).
- **Listeners**: Place in `src/<module>/listeners/` in `*.listener.ts` files (e.g. `user-registered.listener.ts` with `UserRegisteredListener`). Use `@OnEvent(EVENT_CONSTANT)` and inject the handler with the event class type. Do **not** put `@OnEvent` handlers inside services; keep them in dedicated listener classes under `listeners/`.
- **Registration**: Register each listener in the module’s `providers` array (e.g. `providers: [OrdersService, OrderCreatedListener]`).
- **Emitting**: Services that emit inject `EventEmitter2` and call `this.eventEmitter.emit(EVENT_CONSTANT, eventInstance)` or `this.eventEmitter.emitAsync(EVENT_CONSTANT, ...)` when they need to wait for listeners.

## Module Structure
Each feature module lives under `src/<module>/`:
- `*.controller.ts` – routes
- `*.service.ts` – business logic
- `*.repository.ts` – Prisma queries
- `constants/events.constants.ts` – event name constants for this module’s events (imported by emitters and listeners)
- `events/*.event.ts` – event payload classes (for event-emitter)
- `listeners/*.listener.ts` – event listeners (`@OnEvent()`); do not put listeners in services
- `dto/*.dto.ts` – DTOs with validation
- `validators/` – custom validators when needed

Ideally **each module should only have one table connected to it** in the database. If a feature needs multiple tables, consider splitting it into separate modules (e.g. user vs otp).

## DTOs & Validation
- Use `class-validator` decorators on all DTOs
- For “exactly one of A or B” (e.g. email XOR mobile), use `@ValidateIf((o) => !o.mobile)` and `@ValidateIf((o) => !o.email)` with `@IsNotEmpty`
- Add `@ApiProperty` / `@ApiPropertyOptional` on DTO fields for Swagger
- Prefer shared validators in `src/shared/validators/` (e.g. `ExistingEntityRecordValidator` with `inverse` for uniqueness)
- **IMPORTANT**: Entity existence checks (e.g., "user exists", "user not found") should be validated in DTOs using validator decorators, NOT in service methods. Create validators extending `ExistingEntityRecordValidator` and apply them to DTO fields. This ensures validation happens before business logic execution and returns proper 400 status codes.

## Swagger
- Add `@ApiTags` on controllers and `@ApiOperation` on each endpoint
- **Return types**: Always add explicit TypeScript return types to controller methods (e.g. `Promise<RegisterResponseDto>`). The Swagger module will infer success response schemas from these types, so do **not** add `@ApiResponse` decorators for successful (2xx) responses
- **Error responses**: Do **not** add `@ApiResponse` decorators for failing responses (400, 401, 403, 404, etc.); keep the docs focused on success shapes
- Document DTOs with `@ApiProperty` / `@ApiPropertyOptional` (examples, descriptions) so request/response bodies are documented

## Types
- **Shared types** (used in more than one module): place in `src/shared/types/` (e.g. `jwt-payload.type.ts`).
- **Module-specific types** (used only in one module): place in `src/<module>/types/` within that module.

## Shared Code
- `src/shared/validators/existing-entity-record.validator.ts` – reusable “exists” / “unique” validator
- `src/shared/generics/repository.abstract.ts` – base for repositories
- `src/shared/types/` – shared types used across the app
- Extend `BaseRepository` and implement `IEntityExistsRepository` when using `ExistingEntityRecordValidator`

## E2E Tests
- **Test folder structure**: Group tests by folder parallel to the module under test. For each `src/<module>/`, put E2E specs in `test/<module>/` (e.g. `src/user/` → `test/user/`, `src/otp/` → `test/otp/`). Use `../config/...` and `../helpers/...` for shared imports from `test/<module>/`.
- Use `testRequest` from `test/config/request.ts` with `HTTP_METHODS_ENUM`
- `setE2eContext` / `getE2eApp` / `getE2ePrisma` from `test/config/e2e-context.ts` hold the test app and prisma instance
- Clear DB in `beforeEach` for isolation
- Register setup/teardown in `test/config/jest-e2e-setup.ts`

## Code Style
- Use TypeScript strict mode
- Use `async/await`; avoid raw `Promise` chains
- Keep services thin; move complex logic to helpers or domain services
